			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>Meh, my home desktop kicked the bucket last Sunday.  :(<br />
<br />
Power supply fried and I was hoping that would be it, but no such luck.  After replacing it, still no video.  I borrowed my wife's video card and still nothing, and I'm not getting any error code beeps at boot that would signify RAM issues, so I'm pretty certain its the motherboard.  /sigh.<br />
<br />
It was a good machine for 3-4 years though I think.  It has a Geforce 9800 in it from back when they were new if that gives any indication how old the machine was.<br />
<br />
But I guess this provided an opportunity to finally upgrade to a SSD hard drive like a couple of the threads around here keep tempting me.  :p<br />
<br />
So we went ahead and just ordered a new barebones.  Don't have the cash to go nuts on a state of the art gaming machine, but I think this will provide a substantial upgrade nonetheless.  With only brief researches, we went with:<br />
<br />
Barebones w/ AMD Fusion APU (Socket FM2)<br />
  w/ AMD APU A8-5500 (4 x 3.7GHz CPUs - plus Radeon 7560D GPU)<br />
  Asus A88XM-A<br />
  Systems - CPU Fan Only<br />
  8GB DDR3 1600MHz (1 x 8GB - Single Module)<br />
  64GB SATA3 Solid State Drive (SSD)<br />
  Standard Value Mid-Tower Case<br />
  400 Watt Power Supply<br />
  nVidia Geforce GT610 - 1GB<br />
<br />
I'll be using the CDROM and additional fans from my old system and the 650W power supply we just bought to put in this new one.<br />
<br />
Total damage was $450 through PortaTech, who I've used many times in the past with success, which seemed reasonable.<br />
<br />
I'd welcome any pro's or con's about the motherboard, processor and video card we selected if anyone has any though.<br />
<br />
I was a little concerned about how big of a pain it would be transferring my OS over using Windows 8, but holy shit, that was a welcome surprise.  A quick Google search resulted in a very easily found link that I just popped my activation code into and immediately downloaded the setup files, and it also provided the option of temporarily extracting them to a thumb drive and making it bootable.  Schweeet!<br />
<br />
Its supposed to be here late next week.<br />
<br />
:)</div>

